    <item>
      <title>Docker error: error getting credentials</title>
      <link>https://yantonov.com/post/2021-03-06-docker-error-error-getting-credentials/</link>
      <guid>https://yantonov.com/post/2021-03-06-docker-error-error-getting-credentials/</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 06 Mar 2021 21:57:43 +0100</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Aaaah!
Today I faced a strange error message from docker.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt; =&amp;gt; ERROR [internal] load metadata for docker.io/library/python:3.8-slim-buster                                                 0.6s
------
 &amp;gt; [internal] load metadata for docker.io/library/python:3.8-slim-buster:
------
failed to solve with frontend dockerfile.v0: failed to create LLB definition: rpc error: code = Unknown desc = error getting credentials - err: exec: &amp;#34;docker-credential-desktop.exe&amp;#34;: executable file not found in $PATH, out: ``
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;p&gt;Thanks to &lt;a href=&#34;https://forums.docker.com/u/bcheronn&#34;&gt;Bertrand C&lt;/a&gt; for the solution.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;    In ~/.docker/config.json change credsStore to credStore
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://forums.docker.com/t/docker-credential-desktop-exe-executable-file-not-found-in-path-using-wsl2/100225/4&#34;&gt;Source&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Serve dotfiles directly from a git repository</title>
      <link>https://yantonov.com/post/2021-02-13-serve-dotfiles-directly-from-a-git-repository/</link>
      <guid>https://yantonov.com/post/2021-02-13-serve-dotfiles-directly-from-a-git-repository/</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 13 Feb 2021 19:59:18 +0100</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/dotfiles&#34;&gt;Here&lt;/a&gt; is an interesting article which explains another way to store dotfiles.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In a couple of words:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;store dotfiles into a git repository&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;clone your git repository using a bare more and make working directory pointing to ${HOME}&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;use dotfiles directly from the repository (without symbolic links)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The only disadvantage is that all dotfiles must be inside one repository.
It is not scalable approach in that sense that typically configuration files for the different programs are splitted into multiple repositories.
Using multiple repositories helps to effective share particular configurations.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
